snippet.textDisplay:
I had my hair purple for the last few months.. And because of the blue in it, it washed out into an (kinda spotty) mint. Kept it over the holidays because I wanted it to wash out as much as possible before I dye it again but nu-uh. Green is not for me.
Even though I really liked the mint (sadly there's no good picture of it, because my phone color "corrected" it into a more white platinum blonde), but darker green tones look horrible on me (I'm already really pale and sick looking enough lol). Everyone kept complaining that it's green. Every single person. Yea? I KNOW ITS GREEN. Why not? Can't I live in peace for a few weeks with minty green hair? It's not like I don't have a mirror and a pair of functioning eyes and see what colors are going on on my head, Captain Obvious.


But for now (since 2 days, yay) I'm having a flashy red and orange ombre going on (love it, even if it's way more orange than I first wanted it to be). xD


Kinda jealous they're looking so good in those darker greens (especially the second girl, that color is absolutely gorgeous!!) ♥

snippet.textDisplay:
I really hope this year (the year of green), you can do another video of people dying their hair a true green. Not really teal or high blue based greens.

Ive also done green hair a couple times the past few years. Ive always found that most green hair dyes might start green but then after a few washes they will become very teal and blue. Any "emerald" green dyes or artic fox greens are also super teal. So the high level blondes show up super teal. I find that for me, working with a darker blonde, light brown, or yellow tones, will result in a true green.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey, Brad!! I'm not a professional, but I have worked in the beauty industry for years, including hair salons and supply stores and I'm really familiar with Arctic fox. On the first firm, the reason why her ends turned blue is because they were more white than her growth at the top. That particular green actually is a tad on the teal side in real life. So I think where her hair was more Yello, it pulled more green and then those white ends pulled that slightest teal shift in the color. I think she would've gotten more what she wanted if she'd used the color iris green which is more that bright, modori green or she could've stuck with the phantom green, but added in some cosmic sunshine, which is a true, bright yellow. Anyway, as someone who regularly bleaches, treats and has never fried my hair and it's pretty damn healthy and silvery platinum right now, I'm pretty familiar with the whole deposit only dues like Arctic fox, manic panic and ion semi permanent jewel and pastel tones. Sometimes you have to tweak the colors to get what you want. They can be pretty tricky.

snippet.textDisplay: I've used arctic fox's phantom green and it's actually a very blue based green. On white hair it comes out more turquoise blue, it needs more yellow pigment in the hair to stay. Hence why the first girl had green on top and blue on the bottom. This is actually a problem I've experienced with a lot of semi permanent dark greens. Most semi permanent color uses a lot of blue pigment for dark colors. So for dark greens the excessive blue pigment tends to overpower.

snippet.textDisplay: In my experience (2 and a half years with green hair) the reason Jay's hair turned out so blue, is because a lot of darker green dyes tend to be quite blue based. This works out i the consumer's favour, as they don't have to lighten their hair too much, as they can take advantage of the yelllow tones from when they lightened their hair, and they don't have to lighten it as much as they would have to with pink or purple hair.

snippet.textDisplay: The Arctic Fox Phantom Green has strong blue undertones that will fade to blue. So since she had a more vibrant yellow blonde at the roots, the yellow undertone kept the color a more true vivid green. Her ends were almost white and more porous so I'm thinking it couldn't hold onto the stronger green pigment and showed up as blue, showing us more of what it will fade out to.
